<DOCID> 15944 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 9, 1989, Thursday, South Bay Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 13; Column 5 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
88 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH BAY DIGEST: LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
VEHICLE PERMITS RESTRICTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Avalon City Council has imposed a 90-day moratorium on the issuance of new 
vehicle permits in the city. No new permits will be issued for automobiles, 
trucks, motorcycles or golf carts. The only exceptions will be for motorcycles 
and golf carts in retail inventory. 
</P>
<P>
The moratorium, approved Tuesday by a 4-1 vote, will allow the city to complete 
studies of proposed development, impact on streets and roads, and alternatives 
to increasing the numbers of vehicles on the few streets in the one-square-mile 
island city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020989-0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 15951 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 9, 1989, Thursday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 15; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
369 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROLL CALL: THE HOUSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To Kill A Raise 
</P>
<P>
By a vote of 380 to 48, the House passed a resolution (HJ Res 129) disapproving 
pay raises proposed for members of Congress, federal judges and top officials 
of the executive branch. The measure was then adopted by the Senate and sent to 
President Bush for his signature, officially killing the pay raises. The 
increases were proposed in December by a federal commission and sent to Capitol 
Hill on Jan. 9 by then-President Reagan. 
</P>
<P>
Congressional salaries would have risen nearly 51% to $135,000 under the 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
Craig James (R-Fla.), who supported the resolution, said he was glad the House 
did not permit the raises to take effect automatically. "Allowing this absurd 
increase to go into effect without a vote would have constituted an ethical 
atrocity that this body would not have been able to live down," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Pay raise supporter Dan Rostenkowski (D-Ill.), told colleagues: "It's high time 
we stop whipping ourselves" over the pay issue because "each member of this 
house, Democrat and Republican, is worth a salary of $135,000." 
</P>
