<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON VIEW: A SKID ROW BEACON ASKS FOR HELP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY LOU LOPER, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In its six years, Transition House, the place that provides the homeless with 
support and tools to make the transition to mainstream society, has had a 63% 
success rate in its program graduates. Thus, the Skid Row Development 
Corporation and Charles C. Reed, president of Ahmanson Services, are asking for 
greater support Feb. 23 at the party they host at the Los Angeles Athletic 
Club. 
</P>
<P>
Skid Row chairman Alden McKelvey and president Martha Brown Hicks hope for 
generous donations, pointing out that Transition House is a permanent solution 
to homelessness, not astopgap. 
</P>
<P>
The cocktail affair will honor Ralphs Grocery Co. Mayor Tom Bradley and 
Councilman Gilbert Lindsay are honorary co-chairmen. Sue Laris, Bruce Corwin, 
Andrea Van de Kamp, Catherine Hearst, Charles Hathaway, Jim Hill, Hugh Loftus, 
Morris Newman, Stephen Mellinger and Norman Dreyfuss are expected to be on 
hand. 
</P>
<P>
DOWN-HOME: Italian opera will be followed by an "Americana Party" (Virginia 
ham, Vermont turkey, apple pie and cherry cobbler) at the black-tie opening of 
the Music Center Opera's "Tancredi" (all-American cast) at the Dorothy Chandler 
Pavilion Feb. 17. That evening, the Los Angeles Music Center Opera's 1988-89 
season resumes with Marilyn Horne the star in her debut with the company. 
</P>
<P>
Gala and Patron subscribers including Doug Cramer, Tara Colburn, Nicholas and 
Sandra Costla, Nicholas and Janet Ciriello and Milt and Rosemary Okun are 
expected for the party in the Pavilion Restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
DRIVING FORCE: For two decades customers and friends alike have dashed to San 
Juan Capistrano to see Gep (G. R.) Durenberger's new antiques shipments and 
have tea with the popular antiquarian. When he established Gep's Folie at his 
residence, a folly of a building where he brought the decorative arts leaders 
of the world together for seminars, supporters flocked to his lectures. 
</P>
<P>
Then Durenberger was asked to establish the cultural support for San Juan's 
Michael Graves-designed library; he formed the support group Libros Y Artes 
(Books and Arts). Now, he has given his incredible antiques shop to the city of 
San Juan Capistrano for the new Center for the Study of Decorative Arts he's 
directing. 
</P>
<P>
Friends from around the United States and all over California were in San Juan 
Capistrano last weekend to celebrate with Gep at a black-tie gala and to 
premiere the inaugural exhibition, "California Style: Collectors and 
Collections," which is open to the public Tuesdays through Saturdays until May 
6, when the exhibits change. 
</P>
<P>
Leading the admiring crowd at the opening was Stanley Barrows of New York, dean 
emeritus at Parsons School of Art and former chairman of Interior Design at the 
Fashion Institute of Technology in New York. Gep's old pal from Notre Dame, New 
York and Montecito, designer John Saladino, was in the crowd, bringing Lyn and 
Norman Lear, whose house he's redesigning. Gothic collectors and former 
Pasadenans Jack and Jody Pike, now of San Juan Capistrano, beamed over their 
decorative contributions to the evening. 
</P>
<P>
Party chairman Electa Anderson and Gaye Birtcher, Joyce MacRae, Kay Evans and 
Bettie Auerbach made sure the overflow crowd got juggled. Philip and Sandy 
Jacoby, who are building the Marbella Golf and Country Club, donated $25,000 to 
underwrite the night, creating a lot of fun for everyone including Kay (she was 
chairman of exhibits) and Don Evans, Bud Sampson and Freda Weegar, Tom and Lucy 
Hartford, Harrison Negley, Judy and Steven Smith of La Jolla, Sandi and Tom 
Ewing, Dorothy and Don Koll, Gavin and Ninetta Herbert, John Benecke, Barbara 
and William Steinwedell, Marily and Schuyler Haskell and Bob and Lori 
Warmington. 
</P>
<P>
SOCIAL SCENE: Lee Minnelli hosted a luncheon at the Bistro Garden for her New 
York friend Mary Lou (Mrs. Cornelius Vanderbilt) Whitney. Lee was matron of 
honor when Mary Lou married "Sonny" Whitney. Chums gathering included Betty 
Wilson, Giney Milner, Betsy Bloomingdale, Erlenne Sprague, Harriet Deutsch, 
Carolyn Singleton, Frances Bergen, Laura Mako, Rosemarie Stack, Jayne Berger, 
Nancy Denny and Mary Anne Mobley. Bob and Betty Strub also entertained Mary Lou 
at the races at Santa Anita. . . . 
</P>
<P>
When Austine Hearst (Mrs. William Randolph Jr.) headed the Winter Festival 
dinner dance for the Girl Scout Council of Greater New York Tuesday, she sent 
for L.A.'s Father Maurice Chase to deliver the invocation . . . 
</P>
<P>
Shell and Sandra Ausman hosted a dinner at Chasen's to honor Ambassador Crispin 
Tickell, ambassador to the United Nations from Great Britain, and Lady Tickell. 
The ambassador was also introduced by Lester Korn to business leaders at a 
luncheon at the California Club . . . 
</P>
<P>
Ramon Pajares, general manager of the Inn on the Park, London, and his wife 
Jean host a dinner tonight in the Ballroom of the Four Seasons. The five-course 
affair and auction will benefit the Starlight Foundation and will be prepared 
by the Inn on the Park's executive chef, Eric Deblonde and Bruno Loubet, chef 
de cuisine of the hotel's Four Seasons. Sotheby's senior vice president Robert 
C. Woolley will preside over the auction with items from famous British 
companies including Harrods, Wedgwood and Burberry's. 
</P>
<P>
AGENDA: The Natural History Museum opens its doors for the annual members open 
house Friday . . . 
</P>
<P>
At Geary's Beverly Hills "Bridal Fair" Saturday, the top 10 wedding gifts for 
1989 will be revealed as the shop tells brides everything about weddings . . . 
</P>
<P>
Jill St. John will be at Villeroy &amp; Boch this afternoon to celebrate the 
new Beverly Hills store at 338 N. Rodeo Dr. 
</P>
<P>
IN THE BANK: Chairman Pat Smith says Flintridge Sacred Heart Academy in La 
Canada is richer from the Mardi Gras fund-raiser at La Canada Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
off 
</P>
<P>
CELEBRATING LIFE: The late Joan Orr, wife of Verne Orr, former Secretary of the 
U.S. Air Force, succumbed in 1988 to Lou Gehrig's Disease, but before she died, 
she discovered a passion for creative dance -- and its therapeutic value. She 
reassembled the dance class she had led before the Orrs' departure to 
Washington. She also had been president of the Pasadena Arts Council and became 
the first chairwoman of the famed Bella Lewitzky Dance Company. 
</P>
<P>
Thus, the Light-Bringer Project, in association with the Pasadena Arts Council, 
paid tribute to her at Polytechnic School's Garland Auditorium last week, 
documenting her work on videotape ("A Question of Balance: The Life of Joan 
Orr"), showing her conducting classes from her wheelchair just two weeks before 
her death. Jess Marlow, Mrs. Lewitzky, Scripps College President John Chandler 
and Carole Babcock were all on the program. 
</P>
<P>
KEEPING UP: Paulist Boy Choristers of California benefited from the California 
wine festival this week at St. Paul's in Westwood. Funds are for their June 
European tour . . . 
</P>
<P>
Jennifer Goddard and Sylvia Greenspan Lowe chaired the Rainbow Guild's luncheon 
today at Century Plaza Tower . . . Bette L. Smith hosted the late supper after 
the Founders of the American Cinematheque private screening of "Cousins" . . . 
</P>
<P>
Betty White addressed the Intersorority Mothers' Club of UCLA at its 
scholarship benefit luncheon . . . Prof. Haim Harari, new president of the 
Weizmann Institute of Science, was honored at a dinner dance headed by Gerald 
M. Lushing at the Century Plaza Tower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Lee Minnelli, left, hosted luncheon at The Bistro Garden for New Yorker 
Mary Lou (Mrs. Cornelius Vanderbilt) Whitney, center. Also attending the 
intimate gathering was Betsy Bloomingdale. ALAN BERLINER; Photo, June Arnoult 
and Max Factor III were first-nighters at Natural History Museum's "Nomads: 
Masters of Eurasian Steppe" show. 
</P>
