<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: RADIO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal appeals court in New York has altered a lower court's ruling and 
granted a playwright permission to create a musical based on "Amos 'n' Andy" 
radio programs aired before 1948. The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, 
however, upheld a portion of the lower court's ruling that allowed CBS Inc. to 
retain copyrights of the show's scripts written after 1948. Playwright Stephen 
Silverman "will now have ample latitude to proceed with his musical," the court 
stated. Silverman had filed suit against CBS (which aired "Amos 'n' Andy" on 
radio and TV from 1928 to 1966) after the network denied him a license to 
create a Broadway musical based on the popular show. CBS said the material 
infringed its copyright and trademarks, including the characters, as well as 
phrases such as " 'Scuse me for protruding," " 'Splain dat," and "Holy 
Mackral." ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
