<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE BUTCHER: POSSIBILITIES ARE ENDLESS WHEN YOU BUY A WHOLE, CURED PICNIC HAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MERLE ELLIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cooking style has changed a good bit around our house in the past few years, 
largely because there are no longer as many people around the table at dinner 
time. We used to be a clan of four or six or eight, what with parents and 
children and the hungry friends of children. Today, we are usually only two or 
three, except on special occasions when there may be as many as 20, what with 
parents and children and friends of children, and lovers of children and 
children of friends, and lovers of children of friends -- you know what I mean. 
Anyway, most of the time we're not as many around the table as once we were. 
</P>
<P>
Now you might think that fewer people around the table would have changed my 
wife's shopping habits. Cooking habits? Yes. Shopping habits? No. Neva still 
buys meat as if she were cooking for a crowd -- if the price is right, that is. 
It is not at all unusual for me to walk into the house to be greeted with a 
kiss, a hug and a sensual whispered request such as: "Honey, there are six 
chickens in the refrigerator. They were on sale. Would you cut them up and 
package them for me before dinner?" Or, "Honey, Petrini's had a great special 
on pork loin roasts. I got a couple -- do something with them, will you, 
please?" 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Stocking Up on Ham 
</P>
<P>
Throughout the years I have encouraged her to be on the lookout for, and take 
advantage of, meat specials like that, and I am delighted that she does. It 
saves us a fortune on our grocery bill and we eat well. I have also instructed 
her many times on the "how to" of cutting up a chicken and boning out a pork 
loin roast and all the other money-saving how-to techniques we've talked about 
in this column. Yet she doesn't do any of those things. "Honey," she coos, "why 
do you think I married you?" 
</P>
<P>
Ham was her most recent good buy. Picnic ham at 79 cents a pound. She bought 
one for more than six pounds and the price was more than $5. "Do something with 
this, will you, honey," she said, putting her large acquisition on the kitchen 
counter. "I don't want to cook all this at once." 
</P>
<P>
Picnic ham is the cured and smoked front leg of a pig. It has a bit larger 
ratio of bone and fat to lean meat than ham from the hind leg and for that 
reason is always much less expensive and often a very good buy. They are 
usually, however, sold whole, and so often ignored by anybody not cooking for a 
crowd. Never pass by a good buy on picnic ham. There are so many things to do 
with one, even if you're only cooking for one -- or two -- or three. 
</P>
<P>
Most of the meat on a picnic ham lies on one side or the other of the leg bone 
that runs from the hock at the small end to the shoulder joint at the wide end. 
It's a simple matter to run a boning knife along each side of the bone from the 
hock to the shoulder, removing two good-sized pieces of boneless ham from which 
to make all manner of meals. Bake one piece for a small ham dinner with perhaps 
only a ham sandwich or two left over. Slice or dice the other for a ham and 
potato casserole, ham and eggs or a grilled ham-and-cheese sandwich. 
</P>
<P>
Trim the remaining meat off the top and bottom of the bone to cut into cubes 
for creamed ham on toast or to grind for a delicious ham salad spread. The bone 
and hock are ideal for flavoring a pot of red beans and rice, or split pea 
soup. The possibilities are endless. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
NEVA'S CARBONARA 
</P>
<P>
1/4 pound bacon, diced 
</P>
<P>
2 teaspoons olive oil 
</P>
<P>
2 teaspoons butter 
</P>
<P>
1 clove garlic, minced 
</P>
<P>
2 cups leftover picnic ham, cut julienne 
</P>
<P>
1 (8-ounce) package vermicelli spaghetti, cooked al dente and drained 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup grated Parmesan or Romano cheese 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup chopped parsley 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon salt 
</P>
<P>
1/4 teaspoon black pepper 
</P>
<P>
3 eggs, beaten 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup sliced black olives 
</P>
<P>
Brown bacon in heavy skillet over medium high heat until cooked but not crisp. 
Pour off fat and set bacon aside. 
</P>
<P>
To same pan, add oil, butter, garlic and picnic ham. Saute lightly over medium 
heat. Add cooked spaghetti, bacon, cheese, 2 tablespoons parsley, salt and 
pepper. Stir to mix well. Remove from heat. 
</P>
<P>
Pour eggs over and toss quickly to coat spaghetti evenly. Add olives and toss 
again to mix in. Transfer to warm serving platter and sprinkle on remaining 2 
tablespoons parsley. Makes 4 to 6 servings. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
HAM AND POTATO CASSEROLE 
</P>
<P>
Butter 
</P>
<P>
3 or 4 medium potatoes, peeled and sliced thin, cubed or diced 
</P>
<P>
1 onion, peeled and sliced thin, cubed or diced 
</P>
<P>
1 pound leftover ham, sliced thin, diced or cubed 
</P>
<P>
White Sauce 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup shredded Cheddar cheese 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon chopped parsley 
</P>
<P>
Salt, pepper 
</P>
<P>
Butter ovenproof casserole dish and line bottom with layer of potatoes. Top 
with layer of onions. On top of onions place layer of picnic ham. Repeat layers 
of potatoes and onions. 
</P>
<P>
Place last layer of ham neatly around edge of casserole, leaving space in 
middle. Pour on White Sauce, shaking dish gently from time to time so sauce 
mixes thoroughly through layers. Place grated cheese in space left in center of 
casserole and sprinkle with parsley and season to taste with salt and pepper. 
</P>
<P>
Cover with foil tent and bake at 350 degrees 30 minutes. Remove foil and bake 
another 30 minutes. Makes 4 to 6 servings. 
</P>
<P>
Note: serve with beans or greens and corn bread. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
White Sauce 
</P>
<P>
3 tablespoons butter 
</P>
<P>
3 tablespoons flour 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 cups milk 
</P>
<P>
Salt, pepper 
</P>
<P>
Melt butter in saucepan and blend in flour. Stirring continuously, add milk 
slowly. Cook until thickened. Season to taste with salt and pepper. 
</P>
<P>
Note: White Sauce combined with few thinly sliced and sauteed mushrooms and 1 
1/2 cups minced picnic ham may be used for breakfast or brunch, served over 
toasted English muffins or toast fingers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Picnic ham is the cured and smoked front leg of the pig. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
