<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST: LONG BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
PRESERVATION OFFICER WILL REVIEW DEMOLITION PERMITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Requests for demolition permits for buildings more than 50 years old will be 
reviewed by Long Beach's new neighborhood and historic preservation officer, 
the City Council has decided. 
</P>
<P>
The change in the process is being made in an attempt to save more old, 
historic structures in the city. Planning Director Robert Paternoster said that 
the review process will ensure that the city is aware that a historic structure 
might be endangered before it is too late. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020989-0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 16082 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 9, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Long Beach; Part 9; Page 2; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
157 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST: NORWALK; 
</P>
<P>
CERRITOS COLLEGE WILL HOST MAJOR SPEECH TOURNAMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cerritos Community College will host the 15th annual Tabor-Venitsky 
Invitational Speech Tournament on Friday and Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
More than 18 community colleges are expected to participate in the tournament, 
which is aimed at sharpening students' skills for state and national contests 
to be held later in the year. The tournament will begin at 10 a.m. Friday and 
conclude at 6 p.m. Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
Colleges in both Northern and Southern California will compete as well as 
schools from Washington, Utah and Arizona. Between 200 and 300 students are 
expected to compete. 
</P>
<P>
The tournament is not restricted to speech majors, said Mary Lewis, a director 
in the Cerritos College forensic department. "We draw from all majors. Being 
able to speak in an organized and intelligent manner will help you no matter 
what major you are," Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
Individual and team trophies will be awarded to winners and runners-up at the 
conclusion of the competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
