<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WOMEN IN BLUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by Kathie Bozanich and Susan Davis Greene / Los Angeles 
Times; Graphics by Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
State and federal anti-discrimination laws are the only codes governing the 
hiring of women as law enforcement officers. Individual departments can require 
a skills test, but the skills tested must be relevant to the particular job, 
according to the Orange County district attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
The chart below shows the number of law enforcement officers in Orange County. 
The Westminster office of the California Highway Patrol has the highest 
percentage of female sworn officers, the Laguna Beach Police Department the 
highest percentage of women who rank sergeant or above. The La Habra Police 
Department has the lowest percentage of women in the sworn ranks. Many of the 
departments have no women officers ranking sergeant or above. 
</P>
