<P>
Photo, Animal Magnetism Blind and deaf students at the Foundation for the 
Junior Blind got the chance to meet some animals from the Los Angeles Zoo, and 
foundation employee Diane Tarrant was quick to lend a hand -- and an arm. 
Tarrant, who is blind, became chummy with a small boa constrictor with the help 
of zoo docent Marilyn Rudzik. Before being passed around to the students, a 
ferret poked its nose against the grill of its cage. Everything seemed quite 
ducky, especially for Ricky Parral, a blind youth, who smelled his hand after 
petting a new friend. Chana Schwartz took her time feeling the contours of a 
turtle, which did not go unnoticed by a watchful opossum, secure in the arms of 
a docent. The encounter with the animals last week, the first for many of the 
students, was part of the zoo's outreach program. CASSY COHEN / Los Angeles 
Times 
</P>
