<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: BORG SAYS HE TOOK PILLS TO COMBAT UPSET STOMACH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former tennis star Bjorn Borg denied Wednesday that he had tried to commit 
suicide after he was rushed to a hospital in Milan, Italy, unconscious from 
taking sleeping pills. 
</P>
<P>
Borg, the five-time Wimbledon champion from Sweden, who had his stomach pumped 
in the hospital, said he became ill after mixing alcohol and sleeping pills in 
an attempt to combat an upset stomach. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a lot of fuss about nothing," Borg said. "I felt ill because I ate 
something that upset my stomach. Then I drank and then I took sleeping pills. 
After that I can't remember a thing." 
</P>
<P>
A Milan newspaper said that Borg had tried to kill himself after an argument 
with his fiancee, pop singer Loredana Berte. 
</P>
<P>
Said Berte: "Bjorn had an upset stomach, and to help his digestion he drank a 
couple of glasses of whiskey. Then he went to bed, but he couldn't sleep. He 
was tortured by nausea. 
</P>
<P>
"Hoping to get over it with a good sleep, he took a sleeping pill. Obviously 
this formed a deadly cocktail in his stomach." 
</P>
<P>
Hospital officials who treated Borg refused to say how many pills he had 
swallowed, or to comment on whether he had tried to commit suicide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
